Let $p_1 < p_2 < p_3 < \ldots < p_n < \ldots$ be the sequence of primes (with $p_1 := 2$ as usual). Conjecture: There are infinitely many positive integers $n$ for which \begin{eqnarray}
p_n + p_{n + 3} = 2 p_{n + 2}.
\end{eqnarray} Or equivalently, There are infinitely many quadruplets of consecutive primes of the form $$(p, q, p + h,  p + 2h)$$
